01:09:11.410 --> 01:09:13.450 align:middle line:10%
the function of
human civilization,

01:09:13.450 --> 01:09:16.569 align:middle line:10%
communities, all have
the same foundation.

01:09:16.569 --> 01:09:17.979 align:middle line:10%
As above, so below.

01:09:17.979 --> 01:09:20.950 align:middle line:10%
So that the future
of evolution could

01:09:20.950 --> 01:09:24.020 align:middle line:10%
be understood by looking
the past of evolution.

01:09:24.020 --> 01:09:28.430 align:middle line:10%
And that future reveals
we're on the threshold

01:09:28.430 --> 01:09:33.260 align:middle line:10%
of a brand-new
world, because we're

01:09:33.260 --> 01:09:36.740 align:middle line:10%
going to see where the
patterns play themselves out.

01:09:36.740 --> 01:09:40.020 align:middle line:10%
And it really comes down
to a very interesting fact.

01:09:40.020 --> 01:09:45.720 align:middle line:84%
If we look at the evolution of
vertebrates-- fish, amphibians,

01:09:45.720 --> 01:09:49.850 align:middle line:84%
reptiles, birds,
mammals-- we see a jumping

01:09:49.850 --> 01:09:53.040 align:middle line:84%
from one kind of organization
to the next to the next.

01:09:53.040 --> 01:09:57.080 align:middle line:10%
And I say, well, then, the human
evolution, human civilization

01:09:57.080 --> 01:10:02.960 align:middle line:10%
as a multicellular organism,
would, by fractal geometry,

01:10:02.960 --> 01:10:06.690 align:middle line:10%
replicate the
previous evolution.

01:10:06.690 --> 01:10:10.310 align:middle line:10%
So I go, yeah, humans have
been through those levels

01:10:10.310 --> 01:10:11.810 align:middle line:10%
of vertebrate evolution.

01:10:11.810 --> 01:10:14.570 align:middle line:10%
Fish society was
called mariculture.

01:10:14.570 --> 01:10:16.340 align:middle line:10%
They were the first cultures.

01:10:16.340 --> 01:10:20.180 align:middle line:10%
They lived at the water, lived
off the proceeds from the water,

01:10:20.180 --> 01:10:23.980 align:middle line:10%
couldn't go into the land
because they needed the water,

01:10:23.980 --> 01:10:26.350 align:middle line:10%
so they couldn't just
go out into the land.

01:10:26.350 --> 01:10:29.250 align:middle line:84%
So the first cultures
of humans were

01:10:29.250 --> 01:10:32.520 align:middle line:84%
living on the edges of
continents, using the water,

01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:37.367 align:middle line:84%
and also connecting via water
to all the other land sources.

01:10:37.367 --> 01:10:38.700 align:middle line:10%
Then I say, well, what happened?

01:10:38.700 --> 01:10:40.350 align:middle line:10%
That was called the fish phase.

01:10:40.350 --> 01:10:43.020 align:middle line:10%
Then I say, but fish
gave rise to amphibians.

01:10:43.020 --> 01:10:44.140 align:middle line:10%
Say, what did they do?

01:10:44.140 --> 01:10:48.250 align:middle line:84%
They carried the water with them
when they got out of the water

01:10:48.250 --> 01:10:50.280 align:middle line:90%
so they could be on land.

01:10:50.280 --> 01:10:53.190 align:middle line:84%
A tadpole starts as a
swimming, like, fish organism

01:10:53.190 --> 01:10:54.060 align:middle line:90%
in the water.

01:10:54.060 --> 01:10:56.273 align:middle line:84%
But when it turns
into a frog, it

01:10:56.273 --> 01:10:57.690 align:middle line:84%
doesn't have to
live in the water.

01:10:57.690 --> 01:11:00.010 align:middle line:10%
It carries the water
with it in its body.

01:11:00.010 --> 01:11:02.340 align:middle line:10%
So this allowed the next phase.

01:11:02.340 --> 01:11:04.950 align:middle line:10%
You don't have to live where
the water is at the edge.

01:11:04.950 --> 01:11:06.930 align:middle line:10%
Find the water inside--

01:11:06.930 --> 01:11:08.460 align:middle line:10%
agriculture.

01:11:08.460 --> 01:11:10.860 align:middle line:10%
No longer restricted
to the edge.

01:11:10.860 --> 01:11:16.440 align:middle line:10%
You could create food using the
water that you carry with you,

01:11:16.440 --> 01:11:21.840 align:middle line:10%
or you can get viaducts, or
even learn how to make wells.

01:11:21.840 --> 01:11:24.180 align:middle line:10%
And all of a sudden, you're
not restricted to the front.

01:11:24.180 --> 01:11:27.540 align:middle line:10%
So we went from fish society
to amphibian society,

01:11:27.540 --> 01:11:30.120 align:middle line:10%
from mariculture to agriculture.

01:11:30.120 --> 01:11:33.335 align:middle line:10%
And the next level of
evolution was reptiles.

01:11:33.335 --> 01:11:34.710 align:middle line:10%
I go, what was
unique about them?

01:11:34.710 --> 01:11:36.240 align:middle line:10%
They didn't start in the water.

01:11:36.240 --> 01:11:39.420 align:middle line:10%
They were expressly designed
to start on the land,

01:11:39.420 --> 01:11:40.570 align:middle line:10%
live on the land.

01:11:40.570 --> 01:11:45.060 align:middle line:84%
And they were technically
almost digital.

01:11:45.060 --> 01:11:48.660 align:middle line:84%
I mean, their movements, if you
see them, like their heads--

01:11:48.660 --> 01:11:49.650 align:middle line:90%
click.

01:11:49.650 --> 01:11:52.590 align:middle line:90%
Eyes blink.

01:11:52.590 --> 01:11:54.150 align:middle line:90%
It's a mechanism.

01:11:54.150 --> 01:11:56.820 align:middle line:10%
And I go, yeah, it's a machine.

01:11:56.820 --> 01:11:59.115 align:middle line:10%
A reptile is a machine.

01:11:59.115 --> 01:12:00.240 align:middle line:90%
I go, so what was relevant?

01:12:00.240 --> 01:12:02.615 align:middle line:84%
I said, well, it started out
as a little five-inch little

01:12:02.615 --> 01:12:03.940 align:middle line:90%
